Here in Boston we have been living through several consecutive record-breaking snowfalls.  At my house, we have received six feet of snow (nearly two meters) over the past two weeks, and we have more on the way.  In just 14 days, we have set the record for most snowfall in a 30-day and 40-day period, and we are already at almost double the annual average, and it's only mid-February.  Schools, government services, and public transportation have been shut down repeatedly, and the entire city has come to a virtual halt for a couple days on two separate occasions, with a full travel ban in place for all vehicles.  In short, this has been a crazy past couple of weeks.

But with the craziness comes beauty, as our normal bleak winter landscape has been transformed into an arctic wonderland where, when the wind settles down, peace and softness seem to cloak everything around.  This is the brook behind our house, in the midst of one such lull, while the snow was falling steadily, and all the world seemed still and quiet.

Thanks very much for stopping by, and I hope that wherever you are, peace and quiet are winning out over the sound and fury that so often bring so much to ruin.

I blew them off the best I could with a rocket blower while the image was exposing, and then cleaned with a brush and lens cloth in between exposures. title._content: Golden Age of LP Records - Where to Buy LPs in Boston in the 1960s / 1970s.

description._content:
The back of the November 1969 Schwann catalog had an ad for the Harvard Cooperative Society (Coop) stores. The Palmer Street Annex, one block from Harvard Square, had the best selection of records in Boston. They would bet big on new artists displaying huge piles of records stacked on the floor, before anyone knew they were going to be stars - Bruce Springsteen and Jimi Hendrix for example. Prices were also very good. Several other record stores near Harvard Square featured bootleg, imported, and out of print records - some not in the Schwann Catalog.

The day after finals ended in my senior year I went to the Harvard Coop with a friend. He was a foreign student on a full scholarship from his home country and noticed that the receipt for records was identical to the receipt for books - he went on a record buying binge and sent the bill to the embassy (they paid it without question). Neither of us actually graduated after 4 years and we both lived very near Harvard Square for the next 2 years. - record buying continued to interfere with my studies.

(I DID NOT attend Harvard!!!)

description._content:
Blue skies and winter wonderland conditions in a brief break between a couple of Boston's several recent, successive, big blizzards.  We got over nine feet of snow (nearly three meters) this year, setting a new all-time record.  And virtually all of this came in just over a month, beginning in the last few days of January.  This woodland scene, which looks as if it could be high in the Rockies or deep in the Black Forest somewhere, is actually just a couple of minutes' walk from a station on Boston's Orange Line subway.

This is iPhoneography.

title._content: Early 20th Century Art Deco Architecture in Boston Historic District of Aberdeen in Brighton Neighborhood, Daytime Long Exposure

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license: www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Architecture/i... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ This is my favorite building in my neighborhood and I think is the centerpiece of what is known as the Aberdeen Historic District of Boston. I have posted a couple different angles before, but I have always wanted to nail a front on facade, tried a couple times over the years. There were perfect clouds last weekend while a storm was clearing out, so I took advantage and went right to this building for unfinished business, and I figured the historic snow levels would help me get this facade without cars in the frame. There was a benefit from a huge snow bank that went well into the street, as I was able to set up on the bank and get an angle that normally I would have to set up well into the street for. It was really tough, I had to wait out a few delivery people that parked directly in front of the building and a couple people unloading groceries etc. Between that and waiting for the right clouds it took me well over an hour to get this image, luckily I got this single exposure with great clouds and no cars before the clouds disappeared. title._content: Green Tide Pool on Seaside Cliff with North Atlantic Ocean Horizon, Nahant Massachusetts USA

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license: www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Travel/North-Shore-Massachus... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ This was a completely recreational shot. We were down enjoying the sea cliffs on the best Sunday in months, sunny and warm. This was a nice flat spot on the cliff and there was a green tide pool, so it was a no brainer. This is a single image straight out of the camera just with punched up color. A 90 deg angle was perfect for my 100 x 100mm circular polarizer, so I was able to stack a grad ND with only the depth of the standard LEE holder. This allowed me to shoot through three filters at 16mm with barely any vignetting, and I have found that the square circular polarizer typically always works the best at 90 degree rotations anyways. description._content: Buy a print or commercial license: www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Architecture/i... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ I've been watching them build this modern residential tower in East Cambridge on my drives over the Leverett Circle Connector Bridge. Took a walk around the building and decided to go front on with the entrance. Someone from the building came out and asked me what I was doing, once I explained what I was doing they let it ride and I was able to hang out until the best batch of clouds came through. title._content: Foggy Golden Sunrise over Boston Skyline, Beacon Hill, Massachusetts State House, and Charles River Reflection - Cambridge MA USA

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license: www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Skyline-and-Br... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ It was really foggy yesterday morning, so on my way out of town I decided to take Memorial Drive and assess the situation on the Charles. I couldn't even see the Prudential or the Hancock, so that ruled out any Back Bay angles. I ventured down the sidewalk and noticed some intense coloring around downtown and Beacon Hill as the sun broke through the fog. So I scrambled for position and got out the telephoto. For about 10 minutes there was incredible swirling fog and golden light for this angle, and I got 5 frames of varying focal lengths. This was the first frame I took and was the widest. Canon 6d Canon 70-200mm f/4L at 94 LEE Big Stopper (3.0ND) f/20, ISO 50, 120 sec

title._content: Boston Skyline and Charles River Dragon Boats, Cloudy Sunrise over Back Bay and Harvard Bridge with Mirror Reflection from Cambridge MA USA

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Skyline-and-Br... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ I have shot this place a handful of times in the past couple of years. I took a different approach on this one to get some sharper boats and cloud detail. The river was super calm and there was no wind, so it was optimal conditions to get a different take of this subject. I shot with a wide aperture to get a short exposure length, just enough to get the right amount of water blur. Probably due to my lens, there was absolutely no quality loss in sharpness at this wider aperture, and I think it might even look better than stopped down further. I took around 30 frames while the light was perfect, but it soon clouded over. Canon 6d 16-35 f/2.8L II at 27 LEE Little Stopper (1.8 ND) LEE 0.9 Hard GND f/5.6, ISO 100, 5.4 sec

title._content: Looking up Modern Architecture of EF Education First North American Headquarters in Boston with Morning Sunlight and Cloud Movement, Education Circle Cambridge MA USA

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Architecture/i... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ I went to take some long exposures of the sunrise over the Zakim Bridge and Charles River. title._content: Stormy Sunrise over Charlesgate Yacht Club and Charles River with West End Boston Skyline, Cambridge Massachusetts USA

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license: www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Skyline-and-Br... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ The forecast looked good so I headed out super early this morning. Figured I would hit Charlesgate Yacht Club since it's been awhile. Everything looked promising when I arrived but super dark storm clouds started moving through headed out to the ocean. I thought it was all over, but out of stubbornness I figured I would wait it out and see if I could get any color at some point past sunrise. About 40 mins after sunrise the sun was able to hit the clouds, which started breaking, and they caught some great color. Canon 6d Canon 16-35mm f/2.8L II at 16 LEE Little Stopper (1.8ND) LEE 0.9 Hard GND f/16, ISO 50, 150 sec

title._content: Carlton's Wharf East Boston, Boston Skyline over Boston Harbor through Decayed Pilings with Cloud Movement and Clear Water

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Skyline-and-Br... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ I was driving home the other day earlier than usual and as I approached Boston the clouds coming over the city looked incredible. After raining all day there was brief break in the clouds, so I decided to race down to Carlton's Wharf chasing the last bit of light before the clouds once again took over the sun. I hit every light green on the way into East Boston and got there in record time. I was in and out in 15 mins before the heavy rain. The lighting was brutal and I used an umbrella to shade the camera, luckily I was able to barely shade the filter stack without getting the umbrella in the frame. After a quick shot with only a grad ND I realized I needed a polarizer for the water, so I took all the filters out and used only the polarizer to figure out what 90 deg angle would kill the reflection on the water. I then reloaded all filters and dialed in the grad ND through live view. By using the square polarizer in this way, I'm able to carry only one filter holder with three slots, and I can shoot any combination of three filters without any damaging vignetting at 16mm. I typically use these combinations: ND and square CPL that I can spin to any angle, ND filter and CPL at right angle with grad ND on top, or ND with two grad ND's on top. Camera: Canon 6d Lens: Canon 16-35mm f/2.8L II at 16 Filter: LEE Big Stopper (3.0ND) FiIter: LEE 100mm x 100mm CPL (right angle) Filter: LEE 0.9 Hard GND Settings: f/16, ISO 100, 111 secs

description._content: Fujifilm X100S + WCL-X100 Follow my photoblog and my Instagram

Gasson Hall, at the heart of the Boston College campus, as students are beginning to arrive at the end of the summer break.

"Designed by Charles Donagh Maginnis in 1908, the building influenced the development of Collegiate Gothic architecture in North America. Gasson Hall is named after the 13th president of Boston College, Thomas I. Gasson, SJ, considered BC's 'second founder.'  In 1907, newly installed Boston College President Thomas I. Gasson, SJ, determined that BC's cramped, urban campus in Boston's South End was inadequate and unsuited for significant expansion. Inspired by John Winthrop's early vision of Boston as a 'city upon a hill,' he re-imagined Boston College as a world-renowned university and a beacon of Jesuit education. Less than a year after taking office, he purchased the Lawrence farm on Chestnut Hill, six miles west of the city. He organized an international competition for the design of the campus master plan and set about raising funds for the construction of the 'new' university. Two years later, the competition winner was announced and construction began. From a field of entries by some of the most distinguished architects of the day, Charles Donagh Maginnis' proposal for an 'Oxford in America' was selected." [Wikipedia]

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Aerial-Photogr... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ I went up in a helicopter yesterday at sunset for some aerial views of the Boston skyline, doors off. I got a ton of shots but I decided to start with this one. Little bit of everything in this, but I really liked the Boston Harbor Islands in the distance past the skyline and I dig how you can see both the North End and Beacon Hill Neighborhoods to the left and right of downtown respectively. Also, Storrow Drive snaking through the bottom of the image seemed like a good way to anchor the composition. Got really lucky with the perfect conditions for the photo tour. description._content: Buy a print or commercial license www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Architecture/i... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ I've had this building on my list ever since I figured out it had a cool courtyard detail in the back. I finally got around to it yesterday, but I couldn't quite shoot it as I had planned. I had wanted to take it from across the street but a tree was just enough in the way I had to take it from the sidewalk directly in front. The problem was I really needed to be in the street but with cars moving in and out of the spots I had to go as close to the street as possible on the sidewalk. After a couple frames a construction vehicle pulled in and basically blocked me off from the camera, so I ended up finishing off the frames reaching over the fender from the side and I couldn't see the results until I got back to my car. I probably could have squared this up better if I had more time to analyze results and make adjustments, but considering the circumstances I'm lucky I got anything at all. title._content: Boston Skyline over Charles River at Sunrise with Stormy Sky and Water Reflection, Charles River Yacht Club Cambridge Massachusetts USA

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Skyline-and-Br... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ That haze you see in the distance behind the Hancock Tower is a rain storm over the South Shore. I was getting rained on as I set up for this shot but it cleared, which was fortunate. I took a similar angle a couple months back, but it was early in the season and the yacht club wasn't fully outfitted with boats. There was a little more movement to the boats than ideal, but I really needed the extra length on the exposure to smooth the choppy water. Even after 2 minutes you can still see some ripples in the water. I got the peak color in time, but I was so close to missing it. This is an example of the color happening right at sunrise. Canon 6d Canon 16-35mm f/2.8L II at 16 LEE Little Stopper (1.8 ND) LEE 0.9 Hard GND f/8, ISO100, 120 sec

Before the photo: The Trap Music Orchestra, an ~11-piece jazz/trap band, played for about an hour in front of a storefront on Newbury Street. They were good, they drew a crowd, and I doubt they had a permit. Someone called the cops. During the photo: A squad car pulled up. Someone shouted a request for “Straight Outta Compton.” Over a dozen phones shot into the air, not to record what was happening, but what might. It felt like the most natural thing: if something bad was going to happen, people wanted to have it on video. After the photo: No trouble (that I saw). No arrests (that I saw). The crowd and band slowly dispersed while a sense of a rising counter-surveillance state mixed with an expectation of confrontation lingered in the air. 9/19/2015. Image © Dan Meade. description._content: Leaving Long Wharf on a Boston harbour cruise, a short but interesting sightseeing tour of Boston´s inner harbour.

Autumn colors and blue skies reflected in the shimmering surface of Ell Pond, in the heart of Melrose, Massachusetts. Thank you very much for stopping by. If you would like to see more, or if you are interested in buying fine art prints or wall art or licensing any of my work, please visit: www.RobertCrossPhotography.com
I-90/Mass Pike shields with the Prudential Center and John Hancock Tower in the background.
A great 57 degree night in the city.
Sun set and the pretty colors coming out in the city of Cambridge, MA.

I spent most of the day rolling around the MA south shore with Michael Walsh, and we settled on this location for the sunset. These pilings were part of what appears to be an old lifeguard boat launch. It was a really cool little spot, despite the brutal wind! I like this image, but stay tuned for the long exposure version which gives a whole different mood. I'll post that in the next couple of days. Thank you in advance for visiting and commenting! Like my page on Facebook! Select prints now available at My Website!

Lynch Family Skatepark
North Point Park

The last rays of the setting sun are illuminating the tall parts of the Boston Skyline on a clear day as seen from the Skywalk Observatory at the 50th floor of the Prudential Tower. Looking East (a bit Northeast) the bustling center of New England showcases its mix of skyscrapers, churches, and classic brownstone 19th century urban design. The slightly taller glass Hancock Tower dominates the skyline before us. Hancock Tower also used to have an observation deck open to the public, but since September 11th has remained closed out of (unfounded) fear.

Autumn color, morning sidelight, and the calm waters of Ell Pond, at the heart of the town of Melrose, Massachusetts. If you like what you see here, or if you would like to buy fine art prints, please visit: www.RobertCrossPhotography.com Thanks for stopping by, and I hope you have a fantastic weekend.

description._content: The New and Old John Hancock Buildings
Looking up at the John Hancock Building

This is a timestack of a sunset - meaning I took a series of timelapse frames (at 3 second intervals in this case, using the Sony Nex 5T timelapse app), and then stacked them using StarStax to get an effect similar to a long exposure photograph. The sunset wasn't what I was hoping for, but I do really like the effect of the old submerged pier pilings, so I will definitely be trying this again at some point. 

I think I'm in the market for another camera, because doing these timelapses takes up my camera for a good 40 minutes at a time and I'd like another one to use manually while it goes. I am thinking of just getting another Sony Nex - I can probably get a used one for cheap since my camera is a couple years old (especially after the holidays), and then all the lenses etc will be compatible. But, any other recommendations? My main requirements besides overall image quality are for it to be small and lightweight, and for it to have a way to take a series of photos without me touching it - a timelapse or intervalometer script. Last time I looked, sony had the only line of mirrorless cameras with apps like that. Has that changed?

In the afternoon in Somerville, an hour or two before sunset, the clouds looked like they were shaping up to make a spectacular sunset. Even as I was driving out to East Boston to set up this skyline shot, the clouds I could see from the highway looked amazing. But then once I got there, there wasn't actually much of a sunset - it's still a nice scene, but not what I was hoping for. I'll have to try this spot again.
